\begin{align*}
x^2 + y &= 4 \\
x^4 + y^2 &= 10 \\
\end{align*}

Squaring the first equation, we get
\begin{align*}
x^4 + 2x^2y + y^2 &= 16 \\
x^4 + y^2 &= 10 \\
\end{align*}

Subtracting the second equation from the third equation, we get
\begin{align*}
2x^2y &= 6 \\
x^2y &= \boxed{\frac{6}{2} = 3}
\end{align*}

So, the correct answer is 3.

